title: The Pool
description: Pool Opening -- where countless children learned to swim
The building was a place for many meetings for clubs, classes, and conferences.
alt: Image of women at the YWCA gym

title: New Building
description: Germantown YWCA moves to “Administration Building” at 5820 Germantown Ave.

title: Colored Branch
caption: A group stands before the "Colored Branch" of the Germantown YWCA

alt: Image of women at the YWCA pool

title: Maggie Kuhn
description: Maggie Kuhn, later famous for founding the Gray Panthers and activism on many issues, worked at the Germantown - sex education, unionization – mill workers. "A healthy community is one in which the elderly protect, care for, love and assist the younger ones to provide continuity and hope."
There followed a period in time where self-governing clubs in the Association grew and girls became more self-conscious of the "government" of the association as a whole
caption: Women training as part of the Business Office Culture program
alt: Image of the Business Office Culture program

description: National YWCA (YWCA USA) adopts Interracial Charter which affirms commitment to integration; this results in integrated swim classes and events at the Germantown YWCA and eventually the closure of the Settlement Music School branch in the 1960s.
caption: An event at the Germantown YWCA
alt: Image of Germantown YWCA event gathering

title: Center in The Park
description: Founding of Center in the Park which existed in the YWCA building until there wasn't anymore space
alt: Image of Center in the park logo

description: YWCA faces economic issues, declining attendance, minimal programming, issues maintaining the building.
source: Tom Beck from The Chestnut Hill Local
caption: The Germantown YWCA, located in the heart of Germantown's historic district, has sat vacant for decades and remains mired in conflict over who should have the right to develop it.
alt: Image of the Germantown YWCA building and the Pastorius Monument taken from the viewpoint in Vernon Park.

title: Mural
description: “Woman of Germantown” mural completed by artist David McShane, commemorating Maggie Kuhn, Louisa May Alcott, Sadie Tanner Alexander, Sarah Ward McLean, Claire Gamble Herbert, and Dinah.

title: Fire
description: Fire breaks out at the YWCA, no injuries reported but significant internal damage to the building. Since 2006, the building had suffered other fires, structural damage, vandalism, and weathering.
caption: Fire damages former Germantown YWCA near Vernon Park
alt: Image of the Germantown YWCA building during the fire incident with emergency vehicles and firefighters working to make sure the fire is extinguished as the fire hose is still out.

description: YWCA threatened by potential demolition. Cindy Bass rejects Mission First Housing bid on the grounds that it would hurt neighborhood revitalization. Friends for the Restoration of the Germantown YWCA formed by Yvonne Haskins and Emaleigh Doley; group petitions to save the building from demolition. The group was revived in 2021.
caption: A front view picture of the YWCA in Germantown looking upwards from the entance.
alt: image of A front view picture of the YWCA in Germantown

title: Redevelopment
description: Philadelphia Redevelopment Authority selects Pittsburgh-based, Black-owned KBK Enterprises to restore the building. They propose an “adaptive-reuse” project which will convert the YWCA into 1- and 2-bedroom apartments (half market-rate, half affordable), as well as commercial and office spaces on the ground floor.
source: Developer picked for historic Germantown YWCA adaptive reuse project - Curbed Philly
caption: The historic Germantown YWCA will be turned into apartments by out-of-town developer KBK Enterprises

title: Revoking KBK Contract
description: Philadelphia Redevelopment Authority revokes the KBK contract after pressure from community members – KBK “failed to show it had the financial capacity to follow through on the project”  (WHYY) and had not moved forward on the project in six years.
Friends for the Restoration of the Germantown YWCA Building formed
alt: Image of Germantown YWCA Building mural

title: Act 135
description: Ken Weinstein files for conservatorship under Act 135 (Per Chestnut Hill Local, “a 2008 state law that gives neighbors, businesses, and nonprofit organizations the right to ask a court to put blighted property in the hands of a conservator”).
